 of subversive writings that not only indicted communism but were also widely embraced by the Romanian public. The author continues to argue that after the fall of communism and the disappearance of subversive literature, the Romanian public started to devour works of translation. A somewhat different form of censorship arose: state-sponsored censorship was replaced by what Vianu terms a crisis of native writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAuthors, RomanianvInterviews. 0aCensorshipzRomania. 0aCommunism and literaturezRomania. 0aLiterature and societyzRomania. 0aPolitics and literaturezRomania. 0aRomanian literaturey20th centuryxCensorship. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Censorship.2bisacsh1 aVianu, Lidia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865583/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK